{{Infobox television | show_name = Adventure | image = | caption = | show_name_2 = | genre = | creator = | developer = | writer = | director = | creative_director = | presenter = | starring = | judges = | voices = | narrated = [[Charles Collingwood (journalist)|Charles Collingwood]] | theme_music_composer = Bernard Greenwald (as Bernard Green) | opentheme = | endtheme = | composer = | country = [[United States]] | language = [[English language|English]] | num_seasons = 3 | num_episodes = | list_episodes = | executive_producer = | producer = | editor = | location = | cinematography = | camera = | runtime = | company = | distributor = | channel = [[CBS]] | picture_format = | audio_format = | first_run = | first_aired = May 1953 | last_aired = July 1956 | status = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | related = | website = | website_title = | production_website = }}
{{Italic title}}'''''Adventure''''' is a documentary television series that aired on CBS beginning in 1953. The series was produced in collaboration with the [[American Museum of Natural History]] and hosted by [[Charles Collingwood (journalist)|Charles Collingwood]].<ref>Terrace, Vincent (1976). ''The Complete Encyclopedia of Television Programs 1947-1976'' (Vol. 1). South Brunswick and New York: A.S. Barnes and Company. {{ISBN|0-498-01561-0}}.</ref> The program consisted of interviews with scientists and academicians and films of anthropological expeditions.
Individuals appearing in interviews included [[historian]] [[Bernard DeVoto]], [[biologist]] [[Alexander Fleming]], and adventurer [[Sasha Siemel]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045365/episodes "Adventure (1953) - Episode list"] Retrieved 2011-06-15.</ref>
Marcel LaFollette has written, "Production approaches that are now standard practice on ''[[NOVA (TV series)|NOVA]]'' and the [[Discovery Channel]] derive, in fact, from experimentation by television pioneers like [[Lynn Poole]] and [[Don Herbert]] and such programs as ''Adventure'', ''[[Zoo Parade]]'', ''Science in Action'', and the [[The Bell Laboratory Science Series|Bell Telephone System’s science specials]]. These early efforts were also influenced by television’s love of the dramatic, refined during its first decade and continuing to shape news and public affairs programming, as well as fiction and fantasy, today."<ref name=LaFollette02>{{cite journal |title=A Survey of Science Content in U.S. Television Broadcasting, 1940s through 1950s: The Exploratory Years |first=Marcel C. |last=LaFollette |journal=Science Communication |date=September 2002 |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=34–71 |doi=10.1177/107554700202400103 |url=http://scx.sagepub.com/content/24/1/34.abstract }} No free online access.</ref> LaFollette included the program in her 2008 overview of early broadcasting devoted to science popularization.<ref>{{cite book |last=LaFollette |first=Marcel Chotkowski |title=Science on the Air: Popularizers and Personalities on Radio and Early Television |publisher=University of Chicago Press |year=2008 |pages=223–225 |isbn=9780226467597 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XZSy5Qhvqt0C&pg=PA223 }}</ref>
==Broadcast history== The show began its run in May 1953 and was broadcast on late Sunday afternoon. It switched to early Sunday evening (6:00 pm to 7:00 pm) in June 1953. In October 1953, it returned to Sunday afternoon and remained there through July 1956.<ref>Brooks, Tim & Marsh, Earle (2007). ''The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows 1946-Present'' (9th ed.). New York: Ballantine Books. {{ISBN|978-0-345-49773-4}}.</ref>
