{{Infobox book | name = Eternity: Our Next Billion Years | image = Cover_art_for_the_book_Eternity_Our_Next_Billion_Years.jpg | image_size = | caption = | alt = | author = Michael Hanlon | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = USA | language = English | series = Macmillan Science | subject = How mankind and society will develop in the long-term future | genre = Futurology/Science | published = November 25, 2008 | media_type = | pages = 280 | awards = | isbn = 0230219314 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource = | exclude_cover = }}
'''''Eternity: Our Next Billion Years''''' is a non-fiction book which speculates about the future of mankind written by science writer [[Michael Hanlon]]. The book is a combination of non-fiction discussions based on science about what the future might look like, interspersed with more imaginative guesses about what life will look like thousands, and millions of years in the future.<ref name=SFS>{{cite web|last1=Ketchersid|first1=Larry|title=INTERVIEW: Michael Hanlon, Author of Eternity, Our Next Billion Years|url=http://www.sfsignal.com/archives/2009/10/draft-_interview_michael_hanlon_author_of_eternity/|publisher=[[SF Signal]]|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>
''Eternity'' was published on November 25, 2008 by [[Palgrave Macmillan]] as part of the Macmillan Science series.{{fact|date=June 2014}}
==Reception== Critical reception has been mixed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Willmetts|first1=Geoff|title=Eternity: Our Next Billion Years by Michael Hanlon (review)|url=http://www.sfcrowsnest.com/articles/books/2008/Eternity-Our-Next-Billion-Years-by-Michael-Hanlon-13246.php|publisher=SF Crowsnest|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> The ''[[SF Site]]'' gave a positive review and commented that the book was well suited to general audiences and was a good primer for people looking for an introduction to the book's themes.<ref name=SF>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Greg L.|title=Eternity: Our Next Billion Years|url=http://www.sfsite.com/05b/et296.htm|publisher=SF Site|accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref> [[Michael Brooks (science writer)|Michael Brooks]] was more critical of the work, as he felt that it "covers some fascinating ground, but remains only superficially interesting, an hors d'oeuvre rather than the main course. Faced with the prospect of eternity, that's not enough to satisfy."<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Brooks|first1=Michael|title=Review: Eternity: Our next billion years by Michael Hanlon|journal=[[New Scientist]]|date=22 October 2008|volume=200|issue=2679|pages=45|doi=10.1016/S0262-4079(08)62711-6|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0262407908627116|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' was also mixed in their opinion, writing "At its best, Hanlon's book offers the fascination and sense of wonder of good science fiction. At its worst, it reads like an earnest United Nations report on the challenges to be overcome in the 21st century. Luckily, there's more best than worst here."<ref name=Kleiner>{{cite news|last1=Kleiner|first1=Kurt|title=What the hell is eternity, anyway? (Review of Hanlon's book: Eternity: Our Next Billion Years|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/review-eternity-by-michael-hanlon-a-very-brief-history-of-eternity-by-carlos-eire/article4351738/|accessdate=4 June 2015|publisher=Globe and Mail|date=2 February 2010}}</ref>
