In another example below, we have divided the order 12 square into four order 6 squares. Each of the order 6 squares are filled with eighteen small numbers and their complements using bordering technique given by al-Antaki. If we remove the shaded borders of the order 6 subsquares and form an order 8 square, then this order 8 square is again a magic square. In its full generality, we can take any ''m''<sup>2</sup>/2 smaller numbers together with their complements to ''n''<sup>2</sup> + 1 to fill the subsquares, not necessarily in continuous sequence.
